The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Tuesday, February 10, 2004 				 $400-m deal with Ericsson
 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT				 	 Ericsson India MD Jan Campbell (left) with BTVL joint MD Akhil Gupta in New Delhi on Monday. (PTI)																								New Delhi, Feb. 9: Bharti Tele-Ventures Ltd and Ericsson, the largest supplier of mobile systems, today signed a $400-million deal  touted as the first of its kind in the world  to build and manage mega networks. 																								The three-year service agreement with Ericsson stipulates that the equipment vendor will be responsible for the management, maintenance, quality assurance and capacity expansion of AirTel networks in the 13 circles. 																								The initiative is aimed to offer congestion-free networks with seamless coverage and enhanced quality in over 1,650 towns and cities. 																								The move will benefit more than four million existing AirTel customers and also millions of new customers that will be added in the coming years. 																								This partnership will enable AirTel to channel its resources and expertise to its core areas of product innovation, value-added services, marketing, branding and pricing, while simultaneously providing world-class services by leveraging Ericssons expertise in network management. 
